{
  "doc_id": "43875",
  "text": "It has been recently argued, however, that probabilistic models of the role of temporal location in causal selection fall short of accounting for causal reasoning about human actions. For example, [CITATION_1] [CITATION_2] have shown that people tend to favor human actions over physical events as actual causes, irrespective of temporal location and change in probability, while [CITATION_3] have established that, when presented with an opportunity chain, i.e., a causal structure in which an earlier event creates the opportunity for a second event to occur 3 , people judge the latter event to be the actual cause if both events are physical, but judge both events to be actual causes if both events are human actions. The following case serves as a paradigmatic example of an opportunity chain: a man lighting a fire in the forest makes it possible for a gust of wind to spread smoke across the whole forest.",
